diagnoses.name: Drug reaction
diagnoses.description: Adverse reactions to drugs can manifest with a variety of symptoms including thrombocytosis, leukocytosis, tongue erythema, hand edema, and maculopapular rash.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki disease
diagnoses.description: A condition primarily affecting children, characterized by fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, irritation and redness of the eyes, swollen lymph glands, and inflammation of the mouth, lips, and throat.

diagnoses.name: Viral exanthems
diagnoses.description: Viral infections can lead to widespread rashes (exanthems), along with symptoms such as fever, leukocytosis, and thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause a wide variety of symptoms including rash, joint pain, kidney problems, and blood disorders such as leukocytosis and thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced hypersensitivity syndrome
diagnoses.description: A severe reaction to certain medications that includes fever, rash, increased counts of white blood cells (leukocytosis), and organ involvement.

diagnoses.name: Infective endocarditis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the heart valves which can cause fever, rash, symptoms of heart failure, and blood abnormalities including thrombocytosis and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial illness that develops in some people who have strep throat. It features a bright red rash that covers most of the body, fever, and throat pain.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow characterized by an abnormal proliferation of blood cells, including leukocytes, often accompanied by other symptoms such as thrombocytosis and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic fever
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of inadequately treated strep throat or scarlet fever. Symptoms include fever, joint pain, and rash.

diagnoses.name: Toxic shock syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening complication of certain types of bacterial infections. It is often associated with the use of superabsorbent tampons but can also occur with skin infections, burns, and after surgery. Symptoms include fever, rash, and systemic involvement.

diagnoses.name: Measles

diagnoses.name: Rubella
diagnoses.description: Also known as German measles, it is a contagious viral infection best known by its distinctive red rash.

diagnoses.name: Infectious mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Often called mono, this infection is usually caused by the Epstein-Barr virus and results in fever, sore throat, and swollen lymph glands, among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Adenovirus infection
diagnoses.description: A common virus that can cause a range of illnesses, including cold-like symptoms, fever, sore throat, and, in some cases, conjunctivitis and an accompanying rash.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki disease
diagnoses.description: A rare childhood disease that causes the walls of the blood vessels in the body to become inflamed, leading to fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, irritation and redness of the whites of the eyes, swollen lymph nodes, and often a red, swollen tongue.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet fever
diagnoses.description: A bacterial illness that develops in some people who have strep throat. It’s characterized by a bright red rash on the body, fever, and sore throat.

diagnoses.name: Chikungunya fever
diagnoses.description: A mosquito-borne viral disease causing fever and severe joint pain, often accompanied by rash, fatigue, and muscle pain.

diagnoses.name: Zika virus
diagnoses.description: A mosquito-borne virus known for causing flu-like symptoms including mild fever and rash, though it can lead to more serious neurological and birth defects in rare cases.

diagnoses.name: HIV acute infection
diagnoses.description: The early stage of HIV infection, characterized by flu-like symptoms including fever, sore throat, and rash. Lymphadenopathy is also a common finding.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of your skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. Symptoms include fever, sore mouth and throat, fatigue, cough, and burning eyes, followed by skin rash that spreads and blisters.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: SLE can present with psychosis due to neuropsychiatric lupus, hemolytic anemia as part of autoimmune hemolysis, skin manifestations such as an erythematous rash, leukopenia, and fever.

diagnoses.name: Evans Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Evans Syndrome is a rare autoimmune disorder characterized by the combination of autoimmune hemolytic anemia and immune thrombocytopenia, which can occasionally present with leukopenia and fever; neurological manifestations could resemble psychosis.

diagnoses.name: Primary Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Though less common, Sjögren's can present with neurological symptoms, including psychosis, alongside hematological abnormalities such as autoimmune hemolysis and leukopenia, fever, and skin rashes.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.rationale: This condition mimics systemic lupus erythematosus, including symptoms such as psychosis, autoimmune hemolysis, skin manifestations, leukopenia, and fever, but is caused by chronic exposure to certain drugs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: In rare cases, RA can present with systemic features including leukopenia, fever, and vasculitis that might cause skin and neurological manifestations (though psychosis is rare), with a possibility of autoimmune hemolysis.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)
diagnoses.rationale: APS can occasionally lead to neurological manifestations including psychosis, alongside autoimmune hemolytic anemia, leukopenia due to bone marrow involvement, fever, and livedo reticularis, a skin condition.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD features a mixture of symptoms from various connective tissue diseases, including SLE, with possibilities of psychosis, hemolytic anemia, skin eruptions, leukopenia, and fever.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Behçet's disease can occasionally present with neurological symptoms (neuro-Behçet's), skin lesions, fever, and hematological disorders, including anemia and leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Adult Onset Still's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This inflammatory condition can present with high fevers, a distinctive salmon-colored rash, and arthritis, with some cases experiencing leukopenia and hemolysis; however, psychosis is not typically a feature.

diagnoses.name: Paroxysmal Nocturnal Hemoglobinuria (PNH)
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily known for hemolysis, PNH can occasionally cause leukopenia and fever due to bone marrow failure. Psychosis and skin manifestations are not typical but can manifest in response to severe anemia or thromboses.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immune Deficiency
diagnoses.description: An immune disorder that can lead to increased susceptibility to infections including otitis media, and possibly relate to the development of cysts and conditions affecting the autonomic system.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma

diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry mouth leading to oral pain, fatigue, and other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system leading to fatigue, pain, and a wide range of other symptoms, potentially including dysautonomias.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A common nutritional deficiency causing low ferritin levels, fatigue, and may contribute to dysautonomias due to its effects on neurotransmitter synthesis.

diagnoses.name: Oral Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory condition affecting mucous membranes inside the mouth, causing painful patches and open sores.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing a variety of symptoms including oral ulcers, fatigue, and iron-deficiency anemia.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Polyglandular Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare condition characterized by the dysfunction of various glands, leading to a plethora of symptoms including oral pain, skin manifestations, fatigue, and possibly hypoferritinemia due to malabsorption.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by visual disturbances and other aura symptoms followed by a severe headache, often on one side of the head. Patients can experience numbness, phonophobia (sensitivity to sound), scotoma (partial loss of vision), and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Migraine without Aura
diagnoses.description: This common type of migraine does not include the visual disturbances of aura but involves headache, nausea, phonophobia, and sometimes numbness.

diagnoses.name: Tension-Type Headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by bilateral tightening discomfort. It might be associated with stress but doesn't usually cause numbness, phonophobia, scotoma, or nausea.

diagnoses.name: Cluster Headache
diagnoses.description: A condition that produces severe headaches on one side of the head. It can be associated with nasal congestion, watery eyes on the same side as the headache, but less commonly with numbness, phonophobia, scotoma, or nausea.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it can cause symptoms like headache, numbness or weakness, especially on one side of the body, along with possible speech difficulties, but it typically doesn't include phonophobia, scotoma, or nausea.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease affecting the brain and spinal cord, causing symptoms such as numbness, weakness, balance issues, and in some cases, headaches, but less commonly phonophobia, scotoma, or nausea.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Tumors in the brain can cause headaches, nausea, vision problems like scotoma, numbness in parts of the body, and more, depending on the tumor's location and size.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition due to poor blood flow in the posterior circulation of the brain causing dizziness, vision problems including scotoma, weakness, numbness, and occasionally, headache and nausea.

diagnoses.name: Hypertensive Encephalopathy
diagnoses.description: A condition caused by severely high blood pressure that can lead to headaches, nausea, vomiting, seizures, confusion, numbness, and in rare cases, phonophobia or scotoma.

diagnoses.name: Arnold-Chiari Malformation
diagnoses.description: A condition where brain tissue extends into the spinal canal. It can cause headaches, often after coughing or sneezing, along with symptoms such as dizziness, numbness, vision problems like scotoma, balance problems, and sometimes nausea.
